{
  "doc_id": "38349",
  "text": "Huntington disease (HD) is an uncommon autosomal-dominant neurodegenerative disease with both juvenile and adult-onset forms that is characterized by cytosine-adenosineguanine trinucleotide repeats in the short arm of chromosome 4 [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The classic adultonset form, accounting for approximately 90-95% of HD cases, typically presents in patients 40-50 years old with rapidly progressive mental deterioration and choreoathetoid movements [CITATION_3] . The less common juvenile form typically presents in patients younger than 20 years old, and affected patients can have prominent rigidity [CITATION_4] . Although HD is autosomal-dominant, approximately 10-15% of cases are sporadic, which can potentially lead to a delayed diagnosis [CITATION_5] .",
